english:
  title: The Tale of Park
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gwaekheon Minister Kim Mun-jeong rose to prominence through his writings and virtue, serving as a trusted counselor through three reigns. Like the divining stalks and tortoise shell, he resolved the nation's most vexing dilemmas, becoming a pillar of the realm's moral instruction. Yet he kept his household discipline ever more rigorous. His sons rose through the examinations—the eldest died young, while the second, Dun-heon, and third, Song-dang, both ascended to the highest offices, perpetuating the family's eminence. His sons-in-law, the An clan and Park clan, likewise achieved distinction through the civil service—the An as Court Counselor, the Park as Secret Advisor and Royal Scribe. Among their descendants, three grandsons of the An rose through the examinations, and three sons of the Park as well.

    One called Soh-yang, with the courtesy name Jung-gang, was a son of the Park clan, the third in line. Though he passed the National Academy examinations, he repeatedly failed at the higher tests. I grieved for him, and so I record his deeds.

    Jung-gang possessed a lofty and unsullied nature, scorning the pedantic study of texts. He read no books in his leisure, pursued no examination preparations. Yet he regarded those who had passed the exams as beneath his notice. Thus whenever the examinations were held, he would enter the hall carrying only paper, brush, and lamp—no books whatsoever. He would dash off compositions amid laughter and idle talk, never bothering to review his work before casting it aside and departing. Inevitably, he never succeeded.

    Once he reflected: "What difference is there between a true man confined in some narrow corner and a frog at the bottom of a well?" He set his face westward toward the imperial capital. There he wandered through mountains and rivers, beheld the palaces and cities, and his vision grew broad and his spirit expansive—no longer the man of former days, but one who had found what he sought.

    Kan Keok-jang, a high minister of the Western Xia, saw him once and took a liking to him. He lodged Jung-gang in his own house and treated him generously, instructing him in the classical texts. Yet Jung-gang remained indifferent. In time, however, he mastered the northern speech, and when he ventured forth to speak with travelers on the road, they did not know him for a man of Goryeo. He grew somewhat pleased with himself and conceived a desire for office, though none stepped forward to aid him.

    Then among his relatives, one became Regional Inspector of Sannam and employed Jung-gang as a clerk in his office. Once Jung-gang came to the capital bearing dispatches. That very year I too passed the higher examination, and we met at an inn. We passed several days in pleasant conversation before he departed. From that time, I never saw him again.

    Alas! Whether Jung-gang still lives or has passed into death, I know not. Our envoys journey annually to the capital of the great empire, yet not a soul returns with word of him. Why is this? Does he dwell so far that he has no connections in the capital? Does he wander among the common folk, ashamed to be seen by his countrymen? Has he already become one of the ancients, beyond recall? How can eight or nine years pass, with messengers traveling to and fro more than once or twice, yet bring no tidings?

    I was no childhood friend to Jung-gang—I knew his face only at the capital. Yet Song-jeong the Master was my own teacher, and one cannot treat his nephew as an ordinary acquaintance. Thus we dined together, and Jung-gang dared not eat his fill; we wore the same robes, and Jung-gang dared not clothe himself properly. Others saw him as strange and dissolute, but I treated him with sincere respect. Others bound him by convention, but I governed him by principle. Thus Jung-gang himself did not presume to treat me as an ordinary friend.

    The descendants of Gwaekheon prospered greatly in their time. Yet Jung-gang ventured to the Middle Kingdom and never returned. Future generations will not know what manner of man he was. Thus does Jung-gang fade away, leaving no record. And he had no sons!

    I grieve for him deeply. I have set down the bare outline, hoping that someone wise may come to know of it. Should Jung-gang have achieved merit in the Middle Kingdom, and history records him saying "A Park of Goryeo—father such-and-such, mother of such-and-such clan," then perhaps this account need not survive. But if it should prove otherwise, let it serve as reference for those Park descendants who compile the family genealogy.
  footnotes:
    - Song-jeong refers to Lee Saek's own teacher, through whom he was connected to Jung-gang by kinship
    - The divining stalks (蓍) and tortoise shell (龜) were ancient Chinese methods of determining heaven's will, used metaphorically to mean wise counsel
    - The National Academy (Seongggyungwan) was Goryeo's highest educational institution
    - Sannam廉訪司 was an administrative region and its Inspector was a significant position
